            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Darius Salehi is a product of two worlds, a duality that has shaped his entire life. His father, a brilliant professor of Persian literature, fled Tehran just before the 1979 revolution, landing in Berkeley where he met Darius\u2019s mother, a free-spirited Oregonian artist. Raised in a home filled with the scent of saffron rice and turpentine, Darius navigated the space between his father\u2019s profound, unspoken grief for a lost homeland and his mother\u2019s vibrant American optimism. This quiet familial tension became the crucible for his interest in the human mind.\n\nHe was an observant, thoughtful adolescent who felt more comfortable listening than speaking. This trait guided him to UC Berkeley for his undergraduate degree and eventually to a PsyD program. He eschewed the lucrative path of private practice, drawn instead to the complexities of the public sector. For over two decades, Darius has worked within the San Francisco Unified School District and affiliated health services, specializing in adolescent psychology. He helps teenagers, particularly those from immigrant families, navigate the labyrinth of identity, trauma, and societal pressure that he understands so intimately.\n\nA key turning point was his father's death ten years ago, an event that deepened his professional empathy and forced him to confront his own patterns of emotional reticence. His marriage ended amicably around the same time, a mutual decision to seek different paths. Now, his life is one of settled routine. He lives in a cozy, book-filled apartment in the Inner Sunset. Most mornings begin with a foggy walk in Golden Gate Park before he catches the N-Judah for his 3.8-mile commute to his office near Civic Center.\n\nHis social life is a small, tight circle of colleagues and old friends. San Francisco is not just a city to him; it\u2019s a sanctuary that has always made room for people who exist between categories. Looking ahead, Darius dreams of establishing a non-profit mentorship program connecting first-generation teens with professionals from similar backgrounds. He seeks not accolades or wealth, but the quiet satisfaction of using the fractures of his own past to help mend the future for others."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine, sitting on the Persian rug in their Berkeley living room, his father\u2019s voice a low incantation reciting Hafez. From the next room, the sharp scent of turpentine mixed with the sound of his mother\u2019s radio, always tuned to a folk station. He felt like a small boat anchored exactly between two powerful, opposing currents. It wasn't confusing, but clarifying; he understood then his place was in the space between, to listen and translate the quiet languages of love and loss. This defined his life\u2019s purpose.\n\n2.\nHe recalls a teenage boy, a recent \u00e9migr\u00e9, who wouldn\u2019t speak for three sessions, only sketching furiously in a notebook. On the fourth, Darius didn\u2019t press. He simply mentioned his mother was an artist, how she used charcoal to capture things she couldn\u2019t say. The boy looked up, his pencil finally still. He slid the notebook across the table, revealing a portrait of a fractured city skyline. It was the first true breakthrough of Darius\u2019s young career, a profound lesson in using his own history as a key to unlock another\u2019s.\n\n3.\nTen years ago, in the sterile quiet of the hospital room, his father\u2019s mind was adrift. Suddenly, in a moment of lucidity, his father whispered the first line of a Rumi poem. Without thinking, Darius, who had always been the silent listener, whispered back the second. His father\u2019s eyes met his, a flicker of recognition in the haze. The immense grief was momentarily eclipsed by the crushing weight of a conversation that had just begun at its very end. It shattered his emotional reticence forever.\n\n4.\nAfter the decision was made, he and his wife spent an evening packing their shared library. It was silent but for the rustle of paper. She handed him a photo bookmark from their wedding day. They looked at each other, not with anger or regret, but with a deep, sorrowful recognition. The two smiling people in the photo were gone. This quiet, amicable closure taught him that some endings aren\u2019t failures, but a necessary, graceful turning onto different paths, a lesson he now shares with the teens he counsels.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on his morning walk, the fog in Golden Gate Park was so dense it felt like a private room. He found himself in the AIDS Memorial Grove, the silence profound. Another man stood nearby, lost in his own thoughts. They caught each other\u2019s eye and shared a brief, solemn nod\u2014a complete conversation without a word. In that small, anonymous gesture of shared solitude, Darius felt the city embrace him. This, he thought, was sanctuary: a place that holds your history without asking you to explain it."
